State MSM Profile: Ohio

Background & Methods

In 2015-2016, researchers at Emory University partnered with colleagues at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) to develop methods to estimate the number of men who have sex with men (MSM) residing in each county in the United States. Using population and housing data from the American Community Survey and estimates from two peer-reviewed publications (Oster et al., 2015 & Purcell et al., 2012), they derived an indirect estimate of MSM population sizes that took into account both the urbanicity of the county as well as its density of households with a male householder and a male same-sex partner.

The full methodology is published in the Journal of Medical Internet Research - Public Health and Surveillance:

Grey JA, Bernstein KT, Sullivan PS, Purcell DW, Chesson HW, Gift TL, Rosenberg ES. Estimating the population sizes of men who have sex with men in US states and counties using data from the American Community Survey. JMIR Public Health Surveill 2016;2(1):e14. DOI: 10.2196/publichealth.5365

Overview of MSM in Ohio

An estimated 144,366 men who have sex with men (MSM) resided in Ohio in 2013, representing 3.2% of the 4,503,084 MSM in the United States. Of the 4,263,691 adult men of Ohio, 3.4% had had sex with another man in the past 5 years, which was less than the overall percentage of adult men in the United States who were MSM (3.9%).

Most MSM in Ohio resided in central counties of large metropolitan areas (50.2%). Including both central and fringe counties, 69.6% resided in a large metropolitan area.


Percentage of MSM by urbanicity, United States and Ohio, 2013

MSM in Ohio Counties

Among counties or county-equivalent areas in Ohio, Franklin County had the largest population of MSM at 31,220, representing 21.6% of all MSM in the state. Franklin County also had the highest percentage of MSM among adult men in Ohio at 7.2%. This was greater than the percentage for Ohio as a whole, which was 3.4% of adult men.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.



MSM in Ohio Metropolitan Statistical Areas

Columbus Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Columbus MSA had the largest metropolitan population of MSM in Ohio at 40,536, or 28.1% of all MSM in the state. Of the 704,527 adult men in Columbus, an estimated 5.8% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Cleveland-Elyria Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Cleveland-Elyria MSA had a population of 34,650 MSM, or 24.0% of all MSM in Ohio. Of the 755,993 adult men in Cleveland-Elyria, an estimated 4.6% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Cincinnati Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Cincinnati MSA overlaps three states: Indiana, Kentucky and Ohio. The Ohio portion of the MSA had 25,251 MSM, or 17.5% of all MSM in the state and 79.5% of the 31,781 MSM in the MSA. Of 591,182 adult men in the Ohio part of Cincinnati, 4.3% were MSM. This was greater than the overall percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA, which was 4.1% of adult men (31,781 out of 770,623).

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.

The Dayton MSA had a population of 6,886 MSM, or 4.8% of all MSM in Ohio. Of the 295,376 adult men in Dayton, an estimated 2.3% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.

The Akron MSA had a population of 6,240 MSM, or 4.3% of all MSM in Ohio. Of the 262,926 adult men in Akron, an estimated 2.4% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Youngstown-Warren-Boardman Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Youngstown-Warren-Boardman MSA overlaps two states: Ohio and Pennsylvania. The Ohio portion of the MSA had 3,025 MSM, or 2.1% of all MSM in the state and 83.3% of the 3,631 MSM in the MSA. Of 167,364 adult men in the Ohio part of Youngstown-Warren-Boardman, 1.8% were MSM. This was greater than the overall percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA, which was 1.7% of adult men (3,631 out of 211,654).

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.
